    <p:notes-list>
      <li id="泥-vs-娘">
        <p>
          Some authors merge <p:ac h="initials38">娘</p:ac> into 
          <p:ac h="initials38">泥</p:ac>, on the belief that
          they were not pronounced any differently, at least
          by the time the <p:ac>廣韻</p:ac> was written. Nevertheless
          it can be confirmed in the present day there 
          remains a phonemic distinction, in that the 
          <p:ac>反切</p:ac> from 
          <p:ac>廣韻</p:ac>
            form two equivalence classes for 
          <p:ac>泥</p:ac> and
          <p:ac>娘</p:ac>. 
        </p>
      </li>
      <li id="舌上音">
        <p>
          Early re-constructions of Middle Chinese determine these
          initials to be (alveolo-)palatal stops <p:mc>舌面塞音</p:mc>.
          The consensus seems to have settled on these being retroflex,
          after considering they might have emerged from a medial *r
          from Old Chinese. The philological term 
          <p:ac>舌上音</p:ac>, literally meaning
          "above-tongue sound", is itself ambiguous on this matter.
        </p>
      </li>
      <li id="齒上音">
        <p>
          <p:ac>齒上音</p:ac> is a relatively modern appellation for these initials.
          In other texts, this row may simply be called <p:ac>正齒音</p:ac>, mixing it up
          with the next row for the alveolo-palatal sibilants.  <p:ac>正齒音</p:ac> was
          the original Chinese philological term, but only in the 19<sup>th</sup> century 
          did <p:mc>陳澧</p:mc> (in his pioneering work <p:mc>《切韻考》</p:mc>)
          discovered that, what had been called <p:ac>正齒音</p:ac> consisted of two
          sets of initials.  Later investigations revealed that the initials
          in this row (i.e. <p:ac>齒上音</p:ac>) were likely retroflex in the same way as 
          <p:ac>舌上音</p:ac>.
        </p>
      </li>
      <li id="laryngeals">
        <p>
          The consonants 
          are definitely grouped very oddly in this row: 
          we elect to do so to make the table more compact, at the
          same time adhering to established convention from Chinese philology.
          From the modern point of view,
          <p:i>x</p:i>, <p:i>ɣ</p:i> are clearly velars, while 
          <p:i>j</p:i> is a palatal glide.
          (On the other hand, <p:ac>喉音</p:ac> literally
          means "throat sounds".)
          The details are too complicated to get into here, but
          initials referred to by
          <p:ac h="initials38">匣</p:ac>, 
          <p:ac h="initials38">云</p:ac>,
          <p:ac h="initials38">以</p:ac> had gotten mixed up historically
          because of sound mergers, explaining why they all ended up
          being categorized as <p:ac>喉音</p:ac>. However, they are
          distinguishable as (three) equivalent classes in
          <p:ac>反切</p:ac> from the <p:ac>廣韻</p:ac>.
          Many authors, in the modern context,
          categorize these initials into the respective rows for
          velars and palatals. 
        </p>
      </li>
      <li id="半齒音">
        <p>
          <p:ac h="initials38">日</p:ac> is often categorized into the 
          row for <p:ac>正齒音</p:ac>, as those initials there
          were also articulated with the palate.
        </p>
        <p>
          Occasionally, one may still encounter a phonetic description like
          <p:i>nʑ</p:i> for the <p:ac>日</p:ac> initial.
          That is plain wrong as a sound value, because consonant 
          clusters were already lost 
          by the period of Early Middle Chinese, but is meant to suggest
          that it is the precursor to the retroflex that later developed in
          northern Chinese varieties (e.g. <p:py>r-</p:py> in <p:mc>普通話</p:mc>
          which can be pronounced as <p:i>ʐ</p:i>), while southern Chinese varieties
          might have preserved the nasal pronunciation.
        </p>
        <p>
          The philological term <p:ac>半齒音</p:ac>, literally "half-tooth sound", 
          was probably meant to suggest this initial did 
          become a sound like <p:i>ʐ</p:i>
          in later Chinese varieties, 
          as opposed to <p:ac>半舌音</p:ac> (below) meaning "half-tongue sound".
        </p>
        <p>
          The reader may notice too, interestingly enough, in Japanese 
          this initial similarly became <p:jr>z-</p:jr>.
        </p>
      </li>
      <li id="半舌音">
        <p>
          <p:ac h="initials38">來</p:ac> is often categorized into the 
          row for <p:ac>舌頭音</p:ac>.
        </p>
      </li>
    </p:notes-list>
  </s:section>

