          American English does not 
          use the vowel <p:i-narrow>a</p:i-narrow> in native words,
          so a (Mexican) Spanish loanword had to be selected here.
          The pronunciation <p:i-narrow>ˈtʰako(ː)</p:i-narrow> is, 
          according to Wiktionary,
          Canadian English, while American English has
          <p:i-narrow>ˈtʰɑkoʊ</p:i-narrow>.  
        </p>
        <p>
          (Personally I use the Canadian variant
          with the vowel being short at the end; to me this word
          remains un-nativized, in the same way I always pronounce the word
          <em class="word" lang="fr">croissant</em> in the French way.
          Though strictly speaking <em class="spell" lang="es">t</em> 
          in Spanish is unaspirated,
          so I am still not entirely faithful to the source language.)
        </p>
      </li>
      <li id="vowel-ɑ">
        <p>
          <em class="word">top</em> would not be a good example
          for <p:i-narrow>ɑ</p:i-narrow>, if you
          <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cot%E2%80%93caught_merger"
            title="Wikipedia: Cot–caught merger">pronounce the vowel in 
          <em class="word">lot</em> the same as in <em class="word">thought</em></a> 
          <p:i-narrow>ɔ</p:i-narrow>,
          or with lip-rounding <p:i-narrow>ɒ</p:i-narrow>.
          A better example, in both American and 
          <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Received_Pronunciation"
             title="Wikipedia: Received Pronunciation">British 
          pronunciation</a>,
          might be words like <em class="word">father</em>
          and <em class="word">spa</em> that have ‘short’ <em class="spell">a</em>.
        </p>
      </li>
      <li id="vowel-ɐ">
        <p>
          English ‘short’ <em class="spell">u</em> is usually transcribed as 
          <p:i>ʌ</p:i>.  But <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Near-open_central_vowel"
            title="Wikpedia: https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Near-open_central_vowel">
          according to Wikipedia, some speakers pronounce
          this <p:i>ʌ</p:i> as <p:i-narrow>ɐ</p:i-narrow></a>, i.e. with the tongue
          positioned towards the centre of the mouth, and lower 
          like for ‘short’ <em class="spell">a</em>.   
        </p>
        <p>
          (I myself probably pronounce it both ways randomly, 
          although I find it difficult
          to tell the difference aurally either way.) 
        </p>
      </li>
      <li id="vowel-ɔ">
        <p>
          <p:i-narrow>ɔ</p:i-narrow> and <p:i-narrow>ɒ</p:i-narrow> are
          the lip-rounded versions of  
          from <p:i-narrow>ʌ</p:i-narrow> and <p:i-narrow>ɑ</p:i-narrow>
          respectively. <p:mc>邵榮芬</p:mc> uses 
          <p:i-narrow>ɔ</p:i-narrow> and <p:i-narrow>ɒ</p:i-narrow>
          only in the few places: <p:ac>魚</p:ac>&nbsp;<p:i>iɔ</p:i>, 
          versus <p:ac>覃</p:ac>&nbsp;<p:i>ɒm</p:i> and <p:ac>合</p:ac>&nbsp;<p:i>ɒp</p:i>.
        </p>
        <p>
          Either the medial or the coda is sufficient to distinguish these phonemes, 
          fortunately 
          (for otherwise I would struggle to tell the difference in the main vowel!). 
        </p>
      </li>
    </p:notes-list>

  </s:section>

